### Generics in Kotlin

Generics allow classes, interfaces, and functions to operate on types specified by the caller, providing type safety without code duplication.

---

### Generic Classes

```kotlin
class Box<T>(val value: T)

fun main() {
    val intBox = Box(123)       // Box<Int>
    val strBox = Box("Hello")   // Box<String>

    println(intBox.value)  // 123
    println(strBox.value)  // Hello
}
```

---

### Generic Functions

```kotlin
fun <T> identity(value: T): T = value

fun <T> List<T>.secondOrNull(): T? {
    return if (size >= 2) this[1] else null
}

fun main() {
    println(identity(42))       // 42
    println(identity("Kotlin")) // Kotlin
    println(listOf(1, 2, 3).secondOrNull())  // 2
}
```

---

### Type Constraints

```kotlin
// Upper bound
fun <T : Comparable<T>> max(a: T, b: T): T {
    return if (a > b) a else b
}

fun main() {
    println(max(10, 20))        // 20
    println(max("Apple", "Banana"))  // Banana
}
```

---

### Multiple Constraints

```kotlin
interface Printable {
    fun print()
}

fun <T> process(item: T) where T : Comparable<T>, T : Printable {
    if (item > item) { /* ... */ }
    item.print()
}
```

---

### Variance: covariant (out) and contravariant (in)

| Modifier | Description | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| `out` | Producer (covariant) | `List<out T>` |
| `in` | Consumer (contravariant) | `Comparable<in T>` |
| `invariant` | Default (neither) | `MutableList<T>` |

```kotlin
open class Animal
class Dog : Animal()

// Covariant: Producer<T> can be Producer<Subtype>
interface Producer<out T> {
    fun produce(): T
}

// Contravariant: Consumer<T> can be Consumer<Supertype>
interface Consumer<in T> {
    fun consume(item: T)
}
```

---

### Type Projections

```kotlin
fun copy(from: Array<out Any>, to: Array<Any>) {
    for (i in from.indices) {
        to[i] = from[i]
    }
}

fun fill(from: Array<in String>, value: String) {
    for (i in from.indices) {
        from[i] = value
    }
}
```

---

### Star Projection

```kotlin
fun printList(list: List<*>) {
    for (item in list) {
        println(item)
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use declaration-site variance (`out`/`in`) when possible. Use use-site variance (type projections) for individual function signatures.

